metadata.name: Leaky Planetary #22
metadata.description:
Have you ever seen an Aurora?

Every day the phenomenon of the Aurora occurs and when its colorful light appears over the Arctic and Antarctic Circles, it is a signal that thousands of tons of oxygen are escaping from the earth's atmosphere.

It would take billions of years for the atmosphere to completely disappear in those tons. The beautiful aurora phenomenon that many people are expecting to see and enjoy is actually a stark reminder of how fragile our earth is.

metadata.name: XTreeZ #13
metadata.description:
Press 'S' key to save canvas as 800x1200 png
Press 'X' key to add one XTreez

Although XTreeZ trunk and branch growth are predictable, the addition of extra secondary branches and leaves create a striking resemblance to high altitude coniferous trees or bonsai. For this reason, XTreeZ are envisioned in millimeters. Each setting is random and may invoke an atmosphere almost entirely dependent on the suns placement and color.

made with p5js

metadata.name: Dialect: Bold #148
metadata.description:
Dialect: Bold is the wild younger sibling of Dialect. As both Dialect collections are created using a string of text as the main input, "Bold" is also a play on the term used to denote the weight of a font. Many aesthetic decisions were made along the way to completing Dialect. Dialect: Bold is what would have happened had a different path been taken. Complimentary but different. Bold!

Generative abstract artwork that explores forms, shapes, coloring and brushwork.

metadata.name: Florescence #110
metadata.description:
Digitally crafted flowers in pots for virtual window sills.

In the spirit of the piranha plant from the Mario Bros videogame. We wanted to create a project that acknowledges the playful depiction of nature in early videogames by creating a retro futuristic collectible that explores aesthetics over gameplay, whilst preserving the playful energy of these early digital worlds. There are many game elements that have emerged over the years that have become iconic in their own right. Their memorable designs have come to represent the exciting feeling of when we first discovered these worlds, but over time an appreciation for their simple design execution, harmony and balance has emerged. Art can exist in many forms and places including a digital pot plant.

Rarity:

There are a total of 23 hand-drawn and animated sprites divided into 4 groups Firelillies, Flytraps, Quasars and Stargazers and there are 15 possible combinations made from these 4 groups. 18% of the collection is a combination of these 4 groups which we can call random and the remaining 72% is divided between the remaining 14 combinations.


There are 3 possible grid systems 1x1, 3x3 and 4x4 

3% 1x1

40% 3x3

57% 4x4



There are 14 possible placement points for all grids and 76 stem/sprite arragement in total



For the pots and stems there are 11 colors to choose and  no rarities for color combinations.



The flower distribution can be either symmetric or random. 35% symmetric and 65% random



Export options:

Pressing 's' on desktop or holding for 2 seconds will download gif to whatever the current device resolution is. To export at a different resolution open the token in new window by clicking 'open' link under the token image and add "&exportsize=1080" or "&exportsize=2160" to end of the url and hit enter then either hold for 2 seconds or press 's' to create gif and download.

metadata.name: The Face We Had #133
metadata.description:
The Face We Had is a series of generative, moving sculptures attempting to express the artists personal thoughts, experiences and inclinations related to meditative and altered states of consciousness. In a non-descriptive way, the piece aims to reflect the always changing nature of mind through patterns of movement and assemblages of form, color and organic shapes, endlessly revolving around a perceived point of origin.  

Although not intended as literal depictions, the elements interact in a way that could be interpreted as dance-like interactions between thought patterns, mental energy, feelings, fragments of memories and layers of personal identity. 



Interactive features:

space - pause/play
w - wireframe view
d - debug view (compute textures)
s - save screenshot
